This constitutes a collection of scripts to aid in making graphs of various metadata.

   

Short instructions

LemonAid is a workflow compiled of Rmarkdown scripts to help you making graphs of various metadata (like barcharts of cultured bacteria, plant growth promotion tests, plant growth, soil and water abiotic factors, qPCR and biolog ecoplates). Scripts are build further from various R packages. To get started click on the menu’s on the left.

Five steps to get started

  1. You need RStudio, and R-version 3.6.2 for windows, or R-version 3.6.3 for Mac. Execute the RStudio.exe, and also R3.6.2.exe, using the default settings. Another program you want to install is notepad++, you need this to easily see and read .R files.

  2. Make a folder called LemonAid in C:/Users/yourname/Documents. In this folder, place the provided script Initialise.R and the LEM_02_362.zip file. Unzip(“LEM_win362.zip”) and place in your Mananas folder.

  3. Go to the LemonAid folder that you created in step 2. Right click on the file Initialise.R and open with Rstudio. In RStudio, please first check if you are using R 3.6.2 version. For this click, Tools > Global Options > and in the pop-up screen select 64-bit, R 3.6.2. Click Apply, Ok. Now you are ready to run initialise.R

  4. Follow the instructions in the Initialise.R file and execute all steps.
    The last command renv:restore can take 1 hour because it will auto-install all packages, in the meantime you can watch this 15 min video to learn R.

  5. You are now ready to run the scripts and generate graphs! Go to your Mananas folder, and click Mananas.Rproj to open. It is good to first test your install by running the scripts on the Minimal Reproducible Example (MRE) dataset (click on the left pannel submenu’s). When you have practised how it works, you can generate a folder in C:/Users/yourname/Documents/yourname and make the following three subfolders:
    Input: Here you need to put your otu_table.txt and mapping.txt and optionally phylogenetic tree, obtained after running Dada2 (or similar).
    Config: place here the config.yaml file
    Results: Here the results will be auto-written too. Make sure your path is not too long; then png will throw an error…
    Update the config file with the new paths to your input, config, results folders, and customise the config.yaml file for your needs.
    **Hints: to help you structuring your thoughts, and filling in the yaml options file, make for yourself an infographic to visually represent your research questions, and datamatrix. See for examples, the template infographic_template.xlsx in the folder templates.

Configuration

Clean workspace

rm(list=ls()) # remove all objects from your workspace, start clean
     options(warn=-1) # toggle off warnings

Open LemonAid project

Click File > recent projects > you should see here LemonAid.
Click LemonAid, now your console should say something like: Project ‘C:/Users/lucg6943/Documents/LemonAid’ loaded. [renv 0.10.0].
Then you are good to go on.

Snapshot

Run renv::snapshot to see if the lock file is in sync with your project. If it wants to update some things, say y.

renv::settings$snapshot.type("all")
     renv::snapshot()

Load libraries

### libraries
     library(yaml)
     library(icesTAF)
     library(rmarkdown)
     library(renv)

Define the path to your configuration folder

The configuration folder contains the config.yaml file. This file contains all the settings, custom options to run the scripts. So you need to edit this config file with the settings you like.

### Adapt the path to the configuration folder.
     Configuration_file_dir <- "C:/Users/lucg6943/Desktop/anvio_shared/LemonAid2/MRE/Config"  # adapt this path to your configuration folder. Here we test it on the Minimal Reproducible Example (MRE), you find it in your LemonAid folder.

 

Load the config.yaml file (run always)

The two lines below load in your configuration file (config.yaml). You need to adapt the name of the file below to the name of your config.yaml file. In this example, the name is config_LemonAid.yaml, you find it in the Lemonaid folder > MRE > config.

setwd(Configuration_file_dir)
     config = yaml.load_file("./config_LemonAid.yaml")  # you can make different .yaml config files with different settings

 

Preprocessing

Here you load in your dataset, and you can filter which variables you want to plot. Note that Load.Rmd needs to have been run, before any other downstream analyses can be possibly run.

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render("./Load/Load.Rmd",output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/Load_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

 

Boxplots, lineplots and dotcharts for soil physicochemical and qPCR data

This script plots a boxplot, line plot or dotchart graph with or without statistics

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./BoxLineplots/BoxLineplots.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/BoxLineplots_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

 

Bubbleplots for soil physicochemical and qPCR data

This plots a bubbleplot chart

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Bubbleplots/Bubbleplots.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/Bubbleplots_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

 

Charts on a map for soil physicochemical and qPCR data

This plots pie charts on a terrain or street map

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Chartsmap/Chartsmap_new.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/Chartsmap_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

   

Barcharts of cultivable bacteria and plant-growth promotion

I love these color-tool helpers:
Chroma.js Color Palette Helper
VIZ Palette
General tips, colorblind safe
Important: for custom color assignments to phyla during your whole project: edit manually the file function_barcharts_colors.R* in the folder LemonAid > Scripts > Barcharts

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     # Normal
     rmarkdown::render('./Barcharts_species/Barcharts.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/barcharts_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))
     # Facet
     rmarkdown::render('./Barcharts_species/Barcharts_facet.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/barcharts_facet_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))
